1
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,520
He was the phenomenon
of the twenties.

2
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:40,650
When you think that he was
as well-known as Lindbergh...

3
00:00:40,687 --> 00:00:42,791
it's really quite astonishing.

4
00:00:45,390 --> 00:00:48,869
His story reflected the nature
of our civilization...

5
00:00:48,908 --> 00:00:50,795
the character of our times.

6
00:00:50,828 --> 00:00:53,729
Yet it was also
one man's story...

7
00:00:53,772 --> 00:00:57,087
and all the themes
of our culture were there...

8
00:00:57,130 --> 00:00:59,847
heroism, will,
things like that...

9
00:00:59,882 --> 00:01:03,591
but when you look back on it,
it was very strange.

10
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:07,167
Well, it is ironic...

11
00:01:07,208 --> 00:01:10,207
to see how quickly
he has faded from memory...

12
00:01:10,248 --> 00:01:13,411
considering what
an astounding record he made.

13
00:01:13,446 --> 00:01:15,813
He was,
of course, very amusing...

14
00:01:15,846 --> 00:01:19,642
but at the same time
touched a nerve in people...

15
00:01:19,685 --> 00:01:24,921
perhaps in a way in which they
would prefer not to be touched.

16
00:01:24,963 --> 00:01:28,224
It certainly is
a very bizarre story.

17
00:01:41,952 --> 00:01:44,406
The year is 1928.

18
00:01:44,447 --> 00:01:48,243
America, enjoying a decade
of unequaled prosperity...

19
00:01:48,286 --> 00:01:49,780
has gone wild.

20
00:01:49,821 --> 00:01:51,861
The Jazz Age, it is called.

21
00:01:51,901 --> 00:01:55,413
The rhythms are syncopated.
The morals are looser.

22
00:01:55,453 --> 00:01:57,972
The liquor is cheaper,
when you can get it.

23
00:01:58,012 --> 00:02:03,226
It is a time of diverse heroes
and madcap stunts...

24
00:02:03,258 --> 00:02:06,902
of speak-easies
and flamboyant parties.

25
00:02:06,937 --> 00:02:09,620
One typical party occurs
at the Long Island estate...

26
00:02:09,657 --> 00:02:12,853
of Mr. And Mrs.
Henry Porter Sutton...

27
00:02:12,888 --> 00:02:15,822
socialites,
patrons of the arts.

28
00:02:15,864 --> 00:02:17,270
Politicians and poets...

29
00:02:17,303 --> 00:02:20,149
rub elbows
with the cream of high society.

30
00:02:20,182 --> 00:02:23,029
Present at the party
is Scott Fitzgerald...

31
00:02:23,061 --> 00:02:25,297
who is to cast perspective
on the twenties...

32
00:02:25,333 --> 00:02:27,536
for all future generations.

33
00:02:27,573 --> 00:02:28,849
He writes in his notebook...

34
00:02:28,884 --> 00:02:31,731
about a curious little man
named Leon Selwyn, or Zelman...

35
00:02:31,763 --> 00:02:34,610
who seemed clearly
to be an aristocrat...

36
00:02:34,643 --> 00:02:38,984
and extolled the very rich
as he chatted with socialites.

37
00:02:39,025 --> 00:02:41,872
He spoke adoringly of Coolidge
and the Republican Party...

38
00:02:41,905 --> 00:02:44,587
all in an upper-class
Boston accent.

39
00:02:44,624 --> 00:02:46,412
"An hour later,"
writes Fitzgerald...

40
00:02:46,448 --> 00:02:49,294
"I was stunned
to see the same man...

41
00:02:49,327 --> 00:02:51,214
"speaking with
the kitchen help.

42
00:02:51,246 --> 00:02:53,929
"Now he claimed
to be a Democrat...

43
00:02:53,966 --> 00:02:58,667
"and his accent seemed coarse,
as if he were one of the crowd."

44
00:02:58,701 --> 00:03:02,083
It's the first small notice
taken of Leonard Zelig.

45
00:03:02,124 --> 00:03:04,709
Florida, one year later.

46
00:03:04,747 --> 00:03:06,569
An odd incident occurs...

47
00:03:06,603 --> 00:03:09,449
at the New York Yankees'
training camp.

48
00:03:09,482 --> 00:03:11,304
Journalists,
anxious as always...

49
00:03:11,337 --> 00:03:15,330
to immortalize the exploits
of the great home-run hitters...

50
00:03:15,369 --> 00:03:17,256
notice a strange new player...

51
00:03:17,289 --> 00:03:20,135
waiting his turn at bat
after Babe Ruth.

52
00:03:20,168 --> 00:03:22,175
He's listed on the roster
as Lou Zelig...

53
00:03:22,215 --> 00:03:25,563
but no one on the team
has heard of him.

54
00:03:25,606 --> 00:03:26,653
Security guards are called...

55
00:03:26,693 --> 00:03:28,416
and he's escorted
from the premises.

56
00:03:28,454 --> 00:03:33,308
It appears as a small item
in the next day's newspaper.

57
00:03:40,003 --> 00:03:42,369
Chicago, Illinois,
that same year.

58
00:03:42,402 --> 00:03:44,408
There is a private party...

59
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:47,166
at a speak-easy
on the South Side.

60
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:49,305
People from the most
respectable walks of life...

61
00:03:49,344 --> 00:03:52,377
dance and drink bathtub gin.

62
00:03:56,831 --> 00:04:01,107
Present that evening
was Calvin Turner, a waiter.

63
00:04:01,149 --> 00:04:03,996
A lot of gangsters
come in the place.

64
00:04:04,028 --> 00:04:06,875
They're good tippers
and take care of us.

65
00:04:06,908 --> 00:04:09,176
We take care of our customers.

66
00:04:09,212 --> 00:04:12,527
On this particular night,
here's a strange guy coming in.

67
00:04:12,570 --> 00:04:14,261
I'd never seen him before.

68
00:04:14,298 --> 00:04:15,378
So I asked the one
or the other...

69
00:04:15,418 --> 00:04:17,141
I said, "John,
you know this guy?

70
00:04:17,177 --> 00:04:18,671
"You ever seen him?"
So he looks.

71
00:04:18,713 --> 00:04:20,371
"No. I ain't never
seen him before.

72
00:04:20,409 --> 00:04:21,553
"I don't know who he is...

73
00:04:21,593 --> 00:04:23,218
"but I know one thing...
he's a tough-Iooking hombre."

74
00:04:23,256 --> 00:04:24,914
So I looked over, and then...

75
00:04:24,951 --> 00:04:26,358
the next thing,
the guy had disappeared.

76
00:04:26,392 --> 00:04:28,595
I don't know where he went to.

77
00:04:28,630 --> 00:04:30,997
But about this time,
the music starts...

78
00:04:31,030 --> 00:04:33,070
and the band
started playing.

79
00:04:33,110 --> 00:04:36,906
I looked. Here's a colored boy
over there playing trumpet.

80
00:04:36,949 --> 00:04:40,429
Man, he was playing back,
and I looked at the guy...

81
00:04:40,468 --> 00:04:42,736
and I said, "He looks
just like that gangster...

82
00:04:42,771 --> 00:04:47,472
"but the gangster was white,
and this guy is black."

83
00:04:47,506 --> 00:04:50,408
So I don't know
what's happening.

84
00:04:50,482 --> 00:04:54,507
New York City.
It is several months later.

85
00:04:54,544 --> 00:04:58,318
Police are investigating
the disappearance of a clerk...

86
00:04:58,351 --> 00:04:59,758
named Leonard Zelig.

87
00:04:59,791 --> 00:05:01,994
Both his landlady
and his employer...

88
00:05:02,030 --> 00:05:03,753
have reported him missing.

89
00:05:03,790 --> 00:05:08,131
They tell police he was an odd
little man who kept to himself.

90
00:05:08,173 --> 00:05:11,107
Two clues are found in
Zelig's Greenwich Village flat.

91
00:05:11,149 --> 00:05:16,483
One, a photograph of Zelig
with Eugene O'Neill...

92
00:05:16,523 --> 00:05:19,653
and one of him as Pagliacci.

93
00:05:22,602 --> 00:05:27,270
Acting on a tip, they trace
his whereabouts to Chinatown...

94
00:05:27,305 --> 00:05:30,151
where, in the rear
of a Chinese establishment...

95
00:05:30,184 --> 00:05:32,125
a strange-Iooking Oriental...

96
00:05:32,168 --> 00:05:35,483
who fits the description
of Leonard Zelig is discovered.

97
00:05:35,526 --> 00:05:38,842
Suspicious, the detectives
try to pull off his disguise...

98
00:05:38,886 --> 00:05:43,140
but it is not a disguise,
and a fight breaks out.

99
00:05:43,173 --> 00:05:46,816
He is removed by force
and taken to Manhattan Hospital.

100
00:05:46,852 --> 00:05:49,786
In the ambulance,
he rants and curses...

101
00:05:49,827 --> 00:05:52,193
in what sounds
like authentic Chinese.

102
00:05:52,226 --> 00:05:55,454
He is restrained
with a straitjacket.

103
00:05:55,490 --> 00:05:58,805
When he emerges from the car
twenty minutes later...

104
00:05:58,848 --> 00:06:03,288
incredibly, he is no longer
Chinese, but Caucasian.

105
00:06:03,328 --> 00:06:06,175
Bewildered interns place him
in the emergency room...

106
00:06:06,207 --> 00:06:08,094
for observation.

107
00:06:08,127 --> 00:06:11,671
At 7 a.m., Dr. Eudora Fletcher,
a psychiatrist...

108
00:06:11,710 --> 00:06:14,808
makes her usual rounds.

109
00:06:14,845 --> 00:06:17,692
When I first heard
about this emergency case...

110
00:06:17,724 --> 00:06:19,611
I didn't think
anything peculiar...

111
00:06:19,644 --> 00:06:22,491
and when I first
laid eyes on him...

112
00:06:22,523 --> 00:06:28,305
it was a bit strange because
I mistook him for a doctor.

113
00:06:28,345 --> 00:06:31,792
He had a very professional
demeanor about him.

114
00:06:31,832 --> 00:06:33,620
As a young psychiatrist...

115
00:06:33,656 --> 00:06:36,503
Eudora Fletcher is fascinated
by Leonard Zelig.

116
00:06:36,535 --> 00:06:39,698
She convinces the conservative
staff at the hospital...

117
00:06:39,735 --> 00:06:42,451
to allow her to pursue
a study of the new admission.

118
00:06:42,486 --> 00:06:44,787
So, what do you do?

119
00:06:44,821 --> 00:06:46,730
Oh, me? I'm a psychiatrist.

120
00:06:48,021 --> 00:06:51,598
I work mostly
with delusional paranoids.

121
00:06:51,635 --> 00:06:53,610
Tell me about it.

122
00:06:53,651 --> 00:06:55,057
There's not much to tell.

123
00:06:55,091 --> 00:06:57,457
I work mostly
on the continent...

124
00:06:57,490 --> 00:07:00,337
and I've written quite a few
psychoanalytic papers.

125
00:07:00,369 --> 00:07:03,052
I worked with Freud in Vienna.

126
00:07:03,089 --> 00:07:05,772
We broke over the concept
of penis envy.

127
00:07:05,808 --> 00:07:09,670
Freud felt that it
should be limited to women.

128
00:07:09,711 --> 00:07:13,507
It's not that he was
making any sense at all.

129
00:07:13,550 --> 00:07:16,397
It was a conglomeration
of psychological double-talk...

130
00:07:16,429 --> 00:07:18,316
that he had apparently heard...

131
00:07:18,349 --> 00:07:20,519
or was familiar with
through reading.

132
00:07:20,557 --> 00:07:22,379
The funny thing was
his delivery was quite fluid...

133
00:07:22,412 --> 00:07:24,778
and might have been
convincing...

134
00:07:24,812 --> 00:07:27,877
to someone
who did not know any better.

135
00:07:27,915 --> 00:07:30,761
Who was this Leonard Zelig
that seemed to create...

136
00:07:30,794 --> 00:07:32,681
such diverse impressions
everywhere?

137
00:07:32,714 --> 00:07:36,542
All that was known of him
was that he was the son...

138
00:07:36,584 --> 00:07:39,431
of a Yiddish actor
named Morris Zelig...

139
00:07:39,464 --> 00:07:41,252
whose performance as Puck...

140
00:07:41,287 --> 00:07:44,548
in the Orthodox version of
"A Midsummer Night's Dream"...

141
00:07:44,583 --> 00:07:46,949
was coolly received.

142
00:07:46,982 --> 00:07:48,957
The elder Zelig's
second marriage...

143
00:07:48,998 --> 00:07:52,543
is marked by constant violent
quarreling, so much so...

144
00:07:52,581 --> 00:07:55,428
that although the family
lives over a bowling alley...

145
00:07:55,460 --> 00:07:58,526
it's the bowling alley
that complains of noise.

146
00:07:58,563 --> 00:08:02,937
As a boy, Leonard is frequently
bullied by anti-Semites.

147
00:08:02,978 --> 00:08:05,825
His parents,
who never take his part...

148
00:08:05,858 --> 00:08:09,686
and blame him for everything,
side with the anti-Semites.

149
00:08:09,728 --> 00:08:13,502
They punish him often
by locking him in a dark closet.

150
00:08:13,536 --> 00:08:15,423
When they are really angry...

151
00:08:15,455 --> 00:08:18,040
they get into the closet
with him.

152
00:08:18,078 --> 00:08:20,925
On his deathbed,
Morris Zelig tells his son...

153
00:08:20,958 --> 00:08:23,804
that life is a meaningless
nightmare of suffering...

154
00:08:23,837 --> 00:08:28,724
and the only advice he gives him
is to save string.

155
00:08:28,764 --> 00:08:31,415
Though brother Jack
has a nervous breakdown...

156
00:08:31,451 --> 00:08:34,647
and sister Ruth becomes
a shoplifter and alcoholic...

157
00:08:34,682 --> 00:08:37,977
Leonard Zelig appears
to have adjusted to life.

158
00:08:38,009 --> 00:08:40,791
Somehow, he seems to have coped.

159
00:08:40,825 --> 00:08:46,094
And then, suddenly,
increasingly strange behavior.

160
00:08:47,800 --> 00:08:50,450
Fascinated
by the Zelig phenomenon...

161
00:08:50,486 --> 00:08:53,333
Dr. Fletcher arranges
a series of experiments...

162
00:08:53,365 --> 00:08:56,747
and invites the skeptical staff
to observe.

163
00:08:56,789 --> 00:09:02,385
With the doctors watching, Zelig
becomes a perfect psychiatrist.

164
00:09:02,419 --> 00:09:05,735
When two Frenchmen
are brought in...

165
00:09:05,779 --> 00:09:09,520
Zelig assumes their characters
and speaks reasonable French.

166
00:09:09,554 --> 00:09:12,401
In the company
of a Chinese person...

167
00:09:12,433 --> 00:09:15,531
he begins to develop
Oriental features.

168
00:09:15,569 --> 00:09:18,884
By now, word has gotten out
to the press...

169
00:09:18,927 --> 00:09:21,774
and the public, thirsting
for thrills and novelty...

170
00:09:21,806 --> 00:09:24,010
is immediately captivated.

171
00:09:26,894 --> 00:09:29,130
The clamor is so great...

172
00:09:29,165 --> 00:09:32,907
that Dr. Allan Sindell
is forced to issue a statement.

173
00:09:32,940 --> 00:09:35,329
We're beginning
to realize the dimensions...

174
00:09:35,372 --> 00:09:38,371
of what could be the scientific
medical phenomenon of the age...

175
00:09:38,411 --> 00:09:40,712
and possibly of all time.

176
00:09:40,747 --> 00:09:42,983
Fresh stories roll off
the press every day...

177
00:09:43,018 --> 00:09:45,920
about Zelig
and his puzzling condition.

178
00:09:45,961 --> 00:09:49,757
Although the doctors claim
to have the situation in hand...

179
00:09:49,800 --> 00:09:53,061
no two can agree
on a diagnosis.

180
00:09:53,095 --> 00:09:55,484
I'm convinced
it's glandular in nature...

181
00:09:55,527 --> 00:09:57,893
and although there's
no evidence of misfunction...

182
00:09:57,926 --> 00:10:01,187
further tests will show
a problem in the secretions.

183
00:10:01,221 --> 00:10:04,352
It's something he picked up
from eating Mexican food.

184
00:10:04,388 --> 00:10:06,754
This manifestation
is neurological in origin.

185
00:10:06,788 --> 00:10:10,103
This patient is suffering
from a brain tumor...

186
00:10:10,147 --> 00:10:14,848
and I should not be surprised
if within several weeks he died.

187
00:10:14,882 --> 00:10:18,678
We have not been able
to locate the tumor...

188
00:10:18,721 --> 00:10:20,509
but we're still looking.

189
00:10:20,545 --> 00:10:23,959
Ironically,
within two weeks' time...

190
00:10:23,999 --> 00:10:27,795
it is Dr. Birsky himself
who dies of a brain tumor.

191
00:10:27,839 --> 00:10:30,489
Leonard Zelig is fine.

192
00:10:30,622 --> 00:10:33,556
Throughout the weeks
of testing and speculation...

193
00:10:33,597 --> 00:10:35,419
Eudora Fletcher
begins to feel...

194
00:10:35,453 --> 00:10:37,820
that the patient
might be suffering...

195
00:10:37,852 --> 00:10:39,739
not from
a physiological disorder...

196
00:10:39,772 --> 00:10:42,138
but from a psychological one.

197
00:10:42,172 --> 00:10:45,487
It is Zelig's unstable makeup,
she suggests...

198
00:10:45,530 --> 00:10:47,417
that accounts
for his metamorphoses.

199
00:10:47,450 --> 00:10:52,206
The governing board of doctors
is hostile to her notion.

200
00:10:52,249 --> 00:10:54,136
They conclude
that Zelig's malady...

201
00:10:54,168 --> 00:10:57,484
can be traced to poor alignment
of the vertebrae.

202
00:10:57,528 --> 00:11:00,080
Tests prove them wrong...

203
00:11:00,119 --> 00:11:02,987
and cause a temporary problem
for the patient.

204
00:11:04,598 --> 00:11:08,874
Now the press and public
hang on every bit of news...

205
00:11:08,917 --> 00:11:11,818
thoroughly absorbed
in the real-life drama.

206
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:15,504
The continuing saga
at Manhattan Hospital goes on.

207
00:11:15,539 --> 00:11:18,572
This morning, doctors report,
experiments were conducted.

208
00:11:18,610 --> 00:11:21,806
Several women were placed
in proximity to the subject...

209
00:11:21,841 --> 00:11:23,663
but no change occurred...

210
00:11:23,697 --> 00:11:25,420
leading authorities
to conclude...

211
00:11:25,457 --> 00:11:27,213
that the phenomenon
does not occur with women.

212
00:11:27,248 --> 00:11:31,404
Doctors will experiment
with a midget and a chicken.

213
00:11:37,678 --> 00:11:39,979
Leonard Zelig continues
to astound scientists...

214
00:11:40,013 --> 00:11:42,947
at New York's
Manhattan Hospital...

215
00:11:42,989 --> 00:11:45,257
where numerous tests
have led nowhere...

216
00:11:45,292 --> 00:11:47,909
in determining the nature of
this astonishing manifestation.

217
00:11:47,947 --> 00:11:50,793
He is confronted
by two overweight men...

218
00:11:50,826 --> 00:11:53,192
at the request of the doctors.

219
00:11:53,226 --> 00:11:55,592
As the men
discuss their obesity...

220
00:11:55,625 --> 00:11:57,991
an initially reticent Zelig
joins in...

221
00:11:58,025 --> 00:12:01,253
swelling himself
to a miraculous 250 pounds.

222
00:12:01,288 --> 00:12:04,353
Next, in the presence
of two Negro men...

223
00:12:04,391 --> 00:12:07,489
Zelig rapidly
becomes one himself.

224
00:12:07,527 --> 00:12:10,111
What will they think of next?

225
00:12:10,150 --> 00:12:14,851
Meanwhile, Americans all over
have their own reactions.

226
00:12:14,884 --> 00:12:18,397
I wish I could be Lenny Zelig,
the changing man.

227
00:12:18,436 --> 00:12:20,159
I'd be different people.

228
00:12:20,195 --> 00:12:22,366
Someday my wishes
will come true.

229
00:12:22,402 --> 00:12:26,679
Leonard Zelig is
one of the finest gentlemen...

230
00:12:26,722 --> 00:12:29,088
in the United States of America.

231
00:12:29,121 --> 00:12:32,502
He is the cat's pajamas.

232
00:12:32,545 --> 00:12:34,366
Trying a new approach...

233
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:37,334
Dr. Fletcher places the subject
under hypnosis.

234
00:12:37,375 --> 00:12:41,400
Tell me why you assume
the characteristics...

235
00:12:41,438 --> 00:12:43,325
of the person you're with.

236
00:12:43,357 --> 00:12:48,691
- It's safe.
- What do you mean safe?

237
00:12:48,732 --> 00:12:51,579
Safe...

238
00:12:51,612 --> 00:12:54,927
to be like the others.

239
00:12:54,971 --> 00:12:58,767
You want to be safe?

240
00:12:58,810 --> 00:13:01,657
I want to be liked.

241
00:13:03,225 --> 00:13:04,631
Probing Zelig's unconscious...

242
00:13:04,665 --> 00:13:07,511
Dr. Fletcher gradually
puts together the pieces...

243
00:13:07,544 --> 00:13:10,543
of Zelig's behavioral puzzle.

244
00:13:10,582 --> 00:13:12,949
Dividing her time
between the hospital...

245
00:13:12,982 --> 00:13:16,910
and the 42nd-Street Library,
she writes her report.

246
00:13:16,949 --> 00:13:19,315
A closed meeting
