for a cautious outing...

750
00:41:59,312 --> 00:42:03,435
an afternoon at her sister's
house in nearby Teaneck.

751
00:42:03,470 --> 00:42:05,510
Meryl Fletcher
is an aviatrix...

752
00:42:05,550 --> 00:42:07,437
a fine professional pilot.

753
00:42:07,469 --> 00:42:10,316
Eudora Fletcher
is an amateur pilot...

754
00:42:10,349 --> 00:42:12,715
and the afternoon
is spent relaxing...

755
00:42:12,749 --> 00:42:15,497
and retelling
old flying experiences.

756
00:42:17,003 --> 00:42:18,890
As the weeks pass...

757
00:42:18,922 --> 00:42:22,238
Zelig is encouraged
to open up more and more...

758
00:42:22,282 --> 00:42:24,169
to give his own opinions.

759
00:42:24,202 --> 00:42:27,048
What was guarded at first
soon becomes expansive.

760
00:42:27,081 --> 00:42:31,422
I hated my stepmother.
I don't care who knows it.

761
00:42:33,351 --> 00:42:34,758
I love baseball.

762
00:42:34,791 --> 00:42:37,157
It doesn't
have to mean anything.

763
00:42:37,190 --> 00:42:39,579
It's just very beautiful
to watch.

764
00:42:41,637 --> 00:42:45,793
I'm a Democrat.
I always was a Democrat.

765
00:42:47,268 --> 00:42:52,023
Is it OK if I don't agree
with you about that recording?

766
00:42:52,066 --> 00:42:53,953
Of course.

767
00:42:53,986 --> 00:42:57,946
Brahms is just always
too melodramatic for me.

768
00:42:57,985 --> 00:43:00,668
You have to be
your own person...

769
00:43:00,704 --> 00:43:03,071
and make your own
moral choices...

770
00:43:03,104 --> 00:43:05,951
even when they do
require real courage.

771
00:43:05,983 --> 00:43:09,976
Otherwise, you're like
a robot or a lizard.

772
00:43:10,014 --> 00:43:12,599
Are you really going
to marry that lawyer?

773
00:43:12,638 --> 00:43:15,026
I would much rather you didn't.

774
00:43:16,477 --> 00:43:17,883
I don't agree.

775
00:43:17,917 --> 00:43:20,785
I think this guy Mussolini
is a loser.

776
00:43:22,716 --> 00:43:26,326
Are we ever going to make love?

777
00:43:26,362 --> 00:43:27,922
It has been three months...

778
00:43:27,962 --> 00:43:30,809
and the board wishes
to examine the patient.

779
00:43:30,841 --> 00:43:34,637
Dr. Fletcher says Zelig isn't
ready to leave the premises.

780
00:43:34,680 --> 00:43:37,047
The doctors agree
to visit him there.

781
00:43:37,079 --> 00:43:39,926
The date is set...
four days hence.

782
00:43:39,959 --> 00:43:41,846
If progress is insufficient...

783
00:43:41,878 --> 00:43:43,787
she will be removed
from the case.

784
00:43:45,782 --> 00:43:49,097
I was very nervous
because in his waking state...

785
00:43:49,140 --> 00:43:51,987
he never remembered anything
from his trance state...

786
00:43:52,020 --> 00:43:54,386
and I wondered
if there could be some way...

787
00:43:54,419 --> 00:43:56,786
of locking
these two things together.

788
00:43:56,818 --> 00:43:59,185
And then I also was worried...

789
00:43:59,218 --> 00:44:02,065
that if he was
with strong personalities...

790
00:44:02,098 --> 00:44:04,202
he might lose his personality.

791
00:44:04,241 --> 00:44:06,445
Sunday at noon,
the doctors arrive.

792
00:44:06,480 --> 00:44:08,847
They are greeted
by Eudora Fletcher...

793
00:44:08,880 --> 00:44:12,676
and Leonard Zelig and are shown
around the grounds.

794
00:44:12,719 --> 00:44:15,566
Though Dr. Fletcher
is tense and alert...

795
00:44:15,599 --> 00:44:18,445
Leonard Zelig seems calm
and at ease.

796
00:44:18,478 --> 00:44:21,793
Despite the fact that he
is surrounded by physicians...

797
00:44:21,836 --> 00:44:24,203
he does not turn into one.

798
00:44:24,236 --> 00:44:27,083
The encounter appears to be
a resounding success...

799
00:44:27,116 --> 00:44:29,482
when Dr. Henry Mayerson
comments innocently...

800
00:44:29,515 --> 00:44:33,311
about the weather,
saying that it is a nice day.

801
00:44:33,354 --> 00:44:36,669
Zelig tells Dr. Mayerson
that he does not agree...

802
00:44:36,713 --> 00:44:39,080
that it is a nice day.

803
00:44:39,112 --> 00:44:40,999
Dr. Mayerson is taken aback...

804
00:44:41,032 --> 00:44:43,333
at the firmness
of Zelig's conviction.

805
00:44:43,367 --> 00:44:48,123
He points out that the sun
is shining and that it is mild.

806
00:44:48,166 --> 00:44:51,482
Zelig, trained to voice his own
personal opinions fearlessly...

807
00:44:51,525 --> 00:44:53,412
is too aggressive.

808
00:44:53,445 --> 00:44:57,240
He has been molded too far
in the other direction.

809
00:44:57,284 --> 00:44:59,170
He has become
over-opinionated...

810
00:44:59,203 --> 00:45:02,977
and cannot brook any
disagreement with his own views.

811
00:45:03,011 --> 00:45:06,392
I'd taken him too far
in the other direction.

812
00:45:06,433 --> 00:45:09,280
He struck Dr. Mayerson
and several board members...

813
00:45:09,313 --> 00:45:10,719
with a rake.

814
00:45:10,753 --> 00:45:12,640
This wasn't what we wanted...

815
00:45:12,672 --> 00:45:14,941
yet I felt I'd
accomplished something.

816
00:45:14,975 --> 00:45:17,877
If I could have him
two more weeks...

817
00:45:17,919 --> 00:45:20,285
I could do some fine-tuning...

818
00:45:20,318 --> 00:45:23,284
and turn Leonard Zelig
back into his own man.

819
00:45:33,339 --> 00:45:36,568
Dr. Eudora Nesbit Fletcher,
the hero...

820
00:45:36,602 --> 00:45:38,489
or should we say, heroine...
of the hour.

821
00:45:38,522 --> 00:45:40,823
The beautiful and brilliant
young psychiatrist...

822
00:45:40,857 --> 00:45:43,224
never lost faith
in her conviction...

823
00:45:43,256 --> 00:45:45,143
that Leonard Zelig,
the human chameleon...

824
00:45:45,176 --> 00:45:47,063
was suffering
from a mental disorder.

825
00:45:47,095 --> 00:45:48,469
Working with her cousin...

826
00:45:48,503 --> 00:45:50,990
cameraman Paul Deghuee,
the doctor managed...

827
00:45:51,030 --> 00:45:52,917
to keep a vital record
of the proceedings...

828
00:45:52,950 --> 00:45:56,178
including rare footage
of Zelig hypnotized.

829
00:45:56,214 --> 00:45:59,115
The patient and healer
have become fast friends...

830
00:45:59,157 --> 00:46:01,044
and enjoy
one another's company...

831
00:46:01,077 --> 00:46:03,923
even when she's
not working on him.

832
00:46:03,956 --> 00:46:06,803
The result of maintaining
a minority opinion...

833
00:46:06,835 --> 00:46:08,842
is a resounding success
for psychiatry.

834
00:46:08,882 --> 00:46:11,915
Who says women
are just good for sewing?

835
00:46:11,953 --> 00:46:13,295
Now it's on to City Hall...

836
00:46:13,329 --> 00:46:15,216
where the town's
newest celebrities...

837
00:46:15,249 --> 00:46:16,874
are given the key to the city.

838
00:46:16,912 --> 00:46:18,734
We're honored to present...

839
00:46:18,768 --> 00:46:21,517
this key
to New York City to you.

840
00:46:24,047 --> 00:46:26,894
Jimmy Walker
did want to be here...

841
00:46:26,926 --> 00:46:31,235
and sing "Leonard the Lizard,"
but he was just too busy.

842
00:46:33,996 --> 00:46:36,003
After city hall,
Eudora Fletcher...

843
00:46:36,043 --> 00:46:38,345
the beautiful genius
who cured Zelig...

844
00:46:38,379 --> 00:46:40,266
of his science-defying
condition...

845
00:46:40,299 --> 00:46:44,095
is honored by fellow scientists
at New York's Waldorf-Astoria.

846
00:46:44,138 --> 00:46:46,984
Present are luminaries
from all over the world...

847
00:46:47,017 --> 00:46:49,864
not just in the field
of psychiatry...

848
00:46:49,896 --> 00:46:52,743
but physics, biology,
mathematics, and you name it.

849
00:46:52,776 --> 00:46:55,458
Here she is exchanging theories
with Nils Andersen...

850
00:46:55,495 --> 00:46:57,883
the father
of modern blood disease.

851
00:46:57,926 --> 00:47:00,347
Later in the week,
Dr. Fletcher is again honored...

852
00:47:00,389 --> 00:47:03,236
as she gets to christen
her first ship.

853
00:47:03,269 --> 00:47:06,050
Quite a success story
for a little girl...

854
00:47:06,085 --> 00:47:07,579
from the backwoods.

855
00:47:11,396 --> 00:47:12,802
I'm speaking to you...

856
00:47:12,835 --> 00:47:15,289
from the home of
Mrs. Catherine Fletcher.

857
00:47:15,331 --> 00:47:18,177
She's the mother
of Dr. Eudora Fletcher...

858
00:47:18,210 --> 00:47:21,057
the famous psychiatrist
in the news these days.

859
00:47:21,089 --> 00:47:24,885
I'll be asking Mrs. Fletcher...
to begin with...

860
00:47:24,928 --> 00:47:27,775
to tell us something
about what it's like...

861
00:47:27,807 --> 00:47:30,654
to raise a medical genius.

862
00:47:30,687 --> 00:47:33,533
I might ask you about
the many sacrifices...

863
00:47:33,566 --> 00:47:36,827
You've made to put your daughter
through medical school.

864
00:47:36,861 --> 00:47:39,227
Speak right into
the microphones, please.

865
00:47:39,260 --> 00:47:41,235
Sacrifices, we had none.

866
00:47:41,276 --> 00:47:44,504
John was a stockbroker.
We had plenty of money...

867
00:47:44,539 --> 00:47:46,905
and I came from a wealthy
Philadelphia family.

868
00:47:46,939 --> 00:47:50,582
I'm sure that your daughter
always wanted to be a doctor...

869
00:47:50,617 --> 00:47:52,657
ever since she could remember.

870
00:47:52,697 --> 00:47:54,584
I don't think so.

871
00:47:54,617 --> 00:47:57,932
I always thought she
wanted to be a flier...

872
00:47:57,975 --> 00:48:00,822
like her sister Meryl,
and raise a family...

873
00:48:00,855 --> 00:48:02,742
but she was a very moody child.

874
00:48:02,774 --> 00:48:05,621
But a mother always
dreams for her child...

875
00:48:05,653 --> 00:48:08,020
to have the success
your daughter has.

876
00:48:08,053 --> 00:48:10,420
She was a very difficult girl.

877
00:48:10,452 --> 00:48:12,339
Tell me about your husband.

878
00:48:12,372 --> 00:48:13,778
I understand that he is
a simple businessman.

879
00:48:13,812 --> 00:48:15,699
He must be so thrilled
and pleased...

880
00:48:15,732 --> 00:48:19,527
to have his daughter
achieve such recognition.

881
00:48:19,571 --> 00:48:22,886
John had problems... depression.
He drank.

882
00:48:22,929 --> 00:48:25,776
Well, Mrs. Fletcher,
thank you so much...

883
00:48:25,809 --> 00:48:28,525
for speaking with us today.

884
00:48:36,207 --> 00:48:38,628
Here at San Simeon,
glorious dreamland...

885
00:48:38,670 --> 00:48:41,157
of newspaper mogul
William Randolph Hearst...

886
00:48:41,197 --> 00:48:45,091
celebrities from all walks
of society sun or play.

887
00:48:45,132 --> 00:48:47,914
There's Marie Dressler
with Mr. Hearst.

888
00:48:47,947 --> 00:48:50,794
Always a popular guest
at San Simeon...

889
00:48:50,827 --> 00:48:54,623
Miss Dressler accepts a flower
from an ardent admirer.

890
00:48:54,666 --> 00:48:57,512
Along with her is Marion Davies.

891
00:48:57,545 --> 00:49:00,861
When she works, Miss Davies
is always dead serious...

892
00:49:00,905 --> 00:49:03,271
But here,
at this fabulous playground...

893
00:49:03,304 --> 00:49:06,172
She shows us her fun side.

894
00:49:06,215 --> 00:49:09,629
There she is with
you-know-who... Charlie Chaplin...

895
00:49:09,670 --> 00:49:11,644
always kidding.

896
00:49:11,686 --> 00:49:14,685
Although New York
is 3,000 miles away...

897
00:49:14,725 --> 00:49:18,434
Jimmy Walker appears through
Mr. Hearst's enchanted gateway.

898
00:49:18,468 --> 00:49:21,882
Another New Yorker
is Leonard Zelig...

899
00:49:21,924 --> 00:49:23,811
here shown clowning...

900
00:49:23,843 --> 00:49:26,210
with everybody's
favorite cowboy... Tom Mix.

901
00:49:26,242 --> 00:49:28,129
Won't Tony be jealous?

902
00:49:28,162 --> 00:49:30,779
Tony is Tom's horse...

903
00:49:30,817 --> 00:49:33,631
and we always thought
they went everywhere together.

904
00:49:33,664 --> 00:49:35,835
There's that fellow
Chaplin again...

905
00:49:35,871 --> 00:49:38,326
this time with Adolphe Menjou.

906
00:49:38,367 --> 00:49:42,425
There's Claire Windsor
and Delores del Rio...

907
00:49:42,462 --> 00:49:44,949
and a very charming
Eudora Fletcher...

908
00:49:44,990 --> 00:49:47,836
chatting with Hollywood's
newest dancing sensation...

909
00:49:47,869 --> 00:49:49,756
James Cagney.

910
00:49:49,788 --> 00:49:52,155
And what have we here?

911
00:49:52,187 --> 00:49:55,154
Only a beautiful lady
named Carole Lombard.

912
00:49:55,195 --> 00:49:57,464
There's Dr. Fletcher
and Leonard Zelig...

913
00:49:57,498 --> 00:50:01,775
hitting a few with Bobby Jones
on Mr. Hearst's golf course.

914
00:50:01,818 --> 00:50:05,614
Unless Leonard can go back to
his old chameleon personality...

915
00:50:05,657 --> 00:50:10,412
and turn into a golf pro,
I'd bet my money on Bobby.

916
00:50:10,456 --> 00:50:13,324
But who cares,
if they're having fun?

917
00:50:18,421 --> 00:50:23,276
Do you want to give the kids
of this country some advice?

918
00:50:23,316 --> 00:50:26,632
I sure do.
Kids, you got to be yourself.

919
00:50:26,676 --> 00:50:28,497
Don't act like anybody else...

920
00:50:28,531 --> 00:50:31,312
because you think
they have all the answers.

921
00:50:31,346 --> 00:50:35,273
Be your own man, speak up,
say what's on your mind.

922
00:50:35,314 --> 00:50:38,160
Maybe they can't do that
in foreign countries...

923
00:50:38,193 --> 00:50:40,080
but that's the American way.

924
00:50:40,112 --> 00:50:43,908
I used to be a member
of the reptile family...

925
00:50:43,951 --> 00:50:45,860
but I'm not anymore.

926
00:51:28,740 --> 00:51:32,035
Zelig, no longer a chameleon,
is his own man.

927
00:51:32,067 --> 00:51:35,383
His point of view
on politics, art, and love...

928
00:51:35,427 --> 00:51:38,274
is honest and direct.

929
00:51:38,306 --> 00:51:41,622
Though his taste is described
by many as lowbrow...

930
00:51:41,665 --> 00:51:43,552
it is his own.

931
00:51:43,584 --> 00:51:46,431
He is finally an individual,
a human being.

932
00:51:46,464 --> 00:51:49,310
He no longer gives up
his own identity...

933
00:51:49,343 --> 00:51:52,691
to be a safe part
of his surroundings.

934
00:51:52,734 --> 00:51:54,621
His taste wasn't terrible.

935
00:51:54,654 --> 00:51:57,500
He was a man who preferred
watching baseball...

936
00:51:57,533 --> 00:51:59,420
to reading "Moby Dick"...

937
00:51:59,453 --> 00:52:02,768
and that got him off
on the wrong foot...

938
00:52:02,811 --> 00:52:04,698
or so the legend goes.

939
00:52:04,731 --> 00:52:07,097
It was much more
a matter of symbolism.

940
00:52:07,131 --> 00:52:09,977
To the Marxists
he was one thing.

941
00:52:10,010 --> 00:52:12,376
The Catholic Church
never forgave him...

942
00:52:12,409 --> 00:52:13,816
for the Vatican incident.

943
00:52:13,849 --> 00:52:15,256
The American people...

944
00:52:15,288 --> 00:52:18,604
in the throes of the Depression
as they were...

945
00:52:18,648 --> 00:52:21,495
found in him a symbol
of possibility...

946
00:52:21,527 --> 00:52:23,828
of self-improvement
and self-fulfillment.

947
00:52:23,863 --> 00:52:26,710
And of course,
the Freudians had a ball.

948
00:52:26,742 --> 00:52:30,058
They could interpret him
in any way they pleased.

949
00:52:30,101 --> 00:52:31,988
It was all symbolism...

950
00:52:32,020 --> 00:52:35,914
but no two intellectuals
agreed about what it meant.

951
00:52:35,955 --> 00:52:38,410
I don't know if you can call it
a triumph of psychotherapy.

952
00:52:38,451 --> 00:52:41,298
It's more like a triumph
of aesthetic instincts.

953
00:52:41,330 --> 00:52:43,697
Dr. Fletcher's techniques
didn't owe anything...

954
00:52:43,729 --> 00:52:46,096
to then-current schools
of therapy...

955
00:52:46,129 --> 00:52:49,445
but she sensed what was needed
and provided it.

956
00:52:49,488 --> 00:52:51,375
That was, in its way...

957
00:52:51,407 --> 00:52:53,349
a remarkable
creative accomplishment.

958
00:52:53,391 --> 00:52:55,846
When I think about it,
it seems to me his story...

959
00:52:55,887 --> 00:52:59,203
reflected a lot of the
Jewish experience in America...

960
00:52:59,246 --> 00:53:03,522
the great urge to push in
and to find one's place...

961
00:53:03,565 --> 00:53:06,412
and then to assimilate
into the culture.

962
00:53:06,444 --> 00:53:08,997
He wanted to assimilate
like crazy.

963
00:53:16,361 --> 00:53:19,360
Eudora Fletcher's
life has also changed...

964
00:53:19,401 --> 00:53:20,807
from this experience.

965
00:53:20,841 --> 00:53:23,688
For her, fame and recognition
are empty rewards...

966
00:53:23,720 --> 00:53:27,036
and do not live up
to the adolescent fantasies...

967
00:53:27,079 --> 00:53:29,217
that prompted her ambition.

968
00:53:29,254 --> 00:53:32,069
She and her patient
have fallen in love...

969
00:53:32,102 --> 00:53:34,949
and it is no surprise
when she forsakes...

970
00:53:34,981 --> 00:53:36,868
the upwardly-mobile
attorney Koslow...

971
00:53:36,901 --> 00:53:39,934
and announces wedding plans
with Zelig.

972
00:54:32,055 --> 00:54:35,983
It was wonderful to see
my sister and Leonard together.

973
00:54:36,022 --> 00:54:39,337
She drew strength from him.

974
00:54:39,381 --> 00:54:43,658
And they were so much in love
with each other...

975
00:54:43,700 --> 00:54:47,976
and she looked happier
than she had in years.

976
00:54:48,019 --> 00:54:53,255
I remember they decided
to get married in the spring...

977
00:54:53,298 --> 00:54:57,126
and then, of course,
the roof fell in.

978
00:54:58,641 --> 00:55:00,583
Two weeks before the wedding...

979
00:55:00,624 --> 00:55:03,787
an ex-showgirl
named Lita Fox comes forth...

980
00:55:03,823 --> 00:55:07,139
and claims that
she is married to Zelig.

981
00:55:07,183 --> 00:55:10,499
She also claims
to have had his child.

982
00:55:10,542 --> 00:55:13,410
It is an immediate scandal.

983
00:55:16,429 --> 00:55:18,403
We were married a year ago.

984
00:55:18,444 --> 00:55:22,720
He said he was an actor.
He sounded just like one.

985
00:55:22,763 --> 00:55:24,650
I'm in show business, too.

986
00:55:24,682 --> 00:55:27,529
We drove to Baltimore,
and we were married...

987
00:55:27,562 --> 00:55:30,179
and I have a license
to prove it.

988
00:55:30,217 --> 00:55:33,533
He had married her while under
a different personality.

989
00:55:33,576 --> 00:55:35,942
When she read of the plans...

990
00:55:35,976 --> 00:55:37,863
for his forthcoming wedding
to Eudora Fletcher...

991
00:55:37,896 --> 00:55:41,277
she was mortified and
decided to take legal action.

992
00:55:41,318 --> 00:55:44,100
Zelig says he will
fight it in court...

993
00:55:44,134 --> 00:55:48,224
but public opinion begins
subtly to shift away from him.

994
00:55:48,260 --> 00:55:52,220
Clever attorneys portray
Lita Fox as an abandoned woman.

995
00:55:52,259 --> 00:55:56,514
The child is neglected, poor,
and fatherless.

996
00:55:56,546 --> 00:55:59,360
Zelig has sold his life story
to Hollywood...

997
00:55:59,394 --> 00:56:01,695
for a large sum of money.

998
00:56:01,730 --> 00:56:03,671
When the scandal breaks...

999
00:56:03,712 --> 00:56:06,079
the studio demands
its money back.

1000
00:56:06,112 --> 00:56:09,275
Zelig can only return half.
The rest has been spent.

1001
00:56:09,312 --> 00:56:12,606
Outraged, the studio gives him
half his life back.

1002
00:56:12,639 --> 00:56:14,526
They keep the best moments.

1003
00:56:14,558 --> 00:56:18,835
He is left with only his
sleeping hours and mealtimes.

1004
00:56:18,877 --> 00:56:23,186
Zelig is shaken by the scandal,
but it is only the beginning.

1005
00:56:23,228 --> 00:56:25,137
Now another woman
steps forward.

1006
00:56:25,180 --> 00:56:29,140
Helen Gray, a salesgirl
from a Wisconsin gift shop...

1007
00:56:29,178 --> 00:56:32,494
claims that Zelig
is the father of her twins.

1008
00:56:32,538 --> 00:56:37,294
She tells lawyers that he passed
himself off as a fur trapper.

1009
00:56:37,337 --> 00:56:39,703
Zelig has no recollection,
but admits...

1010
00:56:39,736 --> 00:56:43,532
it could have happened
during one of his spells.

1011
00:56:43,575 --> 00:56:45,614
It's the signal
for the floodgates to open.

1012
00:56:45,654 --> 00:56:49,101
He married me
at the First Church of Harlem.

1013
00:56:49,142 --> 00:56:51,824
He told me he was the brother
of Duke Ellington.

1014
00:56:51,861 --> 00:56:55,209
He was the guy
who smashed my car up.

1015
00:56:55,252 --> 00:56:57,139
It was brand-new.

1016
00:56:57,172 --> 00:57:00,018
Then he backed up
over my mother's wrist.

1017
00:57:00,051 --> 00:57:04,807
She's elderly
and uses her wrist a lot.

1018
00:57:04,850 --> 00:57:07,664
He painted my house
a disgusting color.

1019
00:57:07,697 --> 00:57:10,064
He said he was a painter.

1020
00:57:10,096 --> 00:57:12,714
I couldn't believe the results.

1021
00:57:12,752 --> 00:57:15,239
Then he disappeared.

1022
00:57:15,280 --> 00:57:17,189
That Zelig
could be responsible...

1023
00:57:17,231 --> 00:57:20,077
for the behavior of
each personality he assumed...

1024
00:57:20,110 --> 00:57:22,662
means dozens of lawsuits.

1025
00:57:22,702 --> 00:57:25,035
He is sued
for bigamy, adultery...

1026
00:57:25,069 --> 00:57:27,916
automobile accidents,
plagiarism, household damages...

1027
00:57:27,948 --> 00:57:30,468
negligence, property damages...

1028
00:57:30,507 --> 00:57:33,922
and performing unnecessary
dental extractions.

1029
00:57:33,963 --> 00:57:36,864
I would like to apologize
to everyone.

1030
00:57:36,906 --> 00:57:39,753
I'm awfully sorry
for marrying all those women.

1031
00:57:39,786 --> 00:57:41,673
It just... I don't know.

1032
00:57:41,705 --> 00:57:44,552
It just seemed
like the thing to do.

1033
00:57:44,584 --> 00:57:47,431
To the gentleman
whose appendix I took out...

1034
00:57:47,464 --> 00:57:49,830
I don't know what to say.

1035
00:57:49,863 --> 00:57:51,750
If it's any consolation...

1036
00:57:51,782 --> 00:57:54,149
I may still have it
somewhere around the house.

1037
00:57:54,182 --> 00:57:58,458
My deepest apology goes to
the Trokman family in Detroit.

1038
00:57:58,501 --> 00:58:01,816
I never delivered
a baby before in my life...

1039
00:58:01,860 --> 00:58:07,042
and I just thought that
ice tongs was the way to do it.

1040
00:58:07,074 --> 00:58:10,718
Thriving mercilessly on
loopholes and technicalities...

1041
00:58:10,754 --> 00:58:14,234
the American legal profession
has a field day.

1042
00:58:14,273 --> 00:58:16,160
Zelig is branded a criminal.

1043
00:58:16,193 --> 00:58:19,039
Despite Dr. Fletcher's
insistence that he cannot be...

1044
00:58:19,072 --> 00:58:22,551
held responsible for actions
while in his chameleon state...

1045
00:58:22,591 --> 00:58:23,965
it is no use.

1046
00:58:23,998 --> 00:58:27,958
Leonard Zelig sets
a bad moral influence.

1047
00:58:27,997 --> 00:58:30,844
America is a moral country.

1048
00:58:30,877 --> 00:58:34,520
It's a God-fearing country.

1049
00:58:34,556 --> 00:58:40,981
We don't condone scandals...
scandals of fraud and polygamy.

1050
00:58:41,018 --> 00:58:47,475
In keeping with a pure society,
I say, lynch the little Hebe.

1051
00:58:48,504 --> 00:58:50,391
Throughout
the humiliating ordeal...

1052
00:58:50,424 --> 00:58:54,863
Eudora Fletcher stands by
the man she loves, valiantly.

1053
00:58:54,903 --> 00:58:56,790
Privately, she tells friends...

1054
00:58:56,823 --> 00:58:59,670
that she is worried about
Zelig's emotional condition...

1055
00:58:59,702 --> 00:59:02,549
which seems to her
to be deteriorating...

1056
00:59:02,581 --> 00:59:05,777
under the weight
of conservative moral opinion.

1057
00:59:05,813 --> 00:59:08,594
In public, he tries to keep up
an appearance of composure...

1058
00:59:08,628 --> 00:59:10,449
but it is increasingly
difficult.

1059
00:59:10,483 --> 00:59:13,450
It is clear that
he is coming apart...

1060
00:59:13,491 --> 00:59:16,806
when he and Eudora dine
at a Greek restaurant...

1061
00:59:16,849 --> 00:59:21,704
and in the midst of the meal,
Zelig begins to turn Greek.

1062
00:59:26,511 --> 00:59:29,358
He longs desperately
to be liked once again...

1063
00:59:29,391 --> 00:59:32,205
to be accepted, to fit in.

1064
00:59:32,237 --> 00:59:35,368
Public clamor over his morality
reaches a fever pitch...

1065
00:59:35,405 --> 00:59:38,252
and on the eve
of his sentencing...

1066
00:59:38,285 --> 00:59:40,423
Leonard Zelig vanishes.

1067
00:59:47,083 --> 00:59:50,660
This is Chief Inspector
of Police Thomas Dowd...

1068
00:59:50,697 --> 00:59:53,152
with a national
broadcasting news break.

1069
00:59:53,193 --> 00:59:55,080
Leonard Zelig is missing.

1070
00:59:55,113 --> 00:59:57,479
On the eve of his sentencing...

1071
00:59:57,511 --> 01:00:00,478
for an assortment
of crimes and misdemeanors...

1072
01:00:00,519 --> 01:00:03,202
ranging from polygamy to fraud,
he has disappeared.

1073
01:00:03,238 --> 01:00:05,125
We are searching for clues...

1074
01:00:05,158 --> 01:00:07,524
and would appreciate
speaking with anyone...

1075
01:00:07,557 --> 01:00:11,200
who might have any information
leading to his apprehension.

1076
01:00:11,236 --> 01:00:14,050
My sister was just shattered.

1077
01:00:14,083 --> 01:00:18,839
She tried to keep up
a calm front...

1078
01:00:18,882 --> 01:00:21,249
but she was just too upset.

1079
01:00:21,282 --> 01:00:23,169
And she wasn't a person...

1080
01:00:23,202 --> 01:00:26,048
who usually
displayed emotion easily...

1081
01:00:26,081 --> 01:00:28,469
except where Leonard
was concerned.

1082
01:00:31,584 --> 01:00:34,682
Dr. Fletcher and the police
confer daily.

1083
01:00:34,719 --> 01:00:36,606
Together they make
public appeals...

1084
01:00:36,638 --> 01:00:39,485
to anyone who might know
of his whereabouts.

1085
01:00:39,518 --> 01:00:41,884
Apart from several
crank telephone calls...

1086
01:00:41,917 --> 01:00:43,672
there is little response.

1087
01:00:43,709 --> 01:00:47,003
Months go by,
and Zelig is not heard from.

1088
01:00:47,036 --> 01:00:48,442
Cars are searched.

1089
01:00:48,475 --> 01:00:51,158
False leads pour in
from everywhere.

1090
01:00:51,194 --> 01:00:53,582
His jacket is recovered
in Texas.

1091
01:00:53,626 --> 01:00:56,472
A manhunt in that state
proves futile.

1092
01:00:56,505 --> 01:00:59,701
He is reported seen
in Chicago, in California.

1093
01:00:59,736 --> 01:01:03,412
This still photo appears
to have a man resembling him...

1094
01:01:03,448 --> 01:01:05,836
with a mariachi band in Mexico.

1095
01:01:09,174 --> 01:01:12,075
Dr. Fletcher continues
to search for Zelig...

1096
01:01:12,117 --> 01:01:14,964
but hopes fade
with each passing day.

1097
01:01:14,996 --> 01:01:18,312
All I could think of
was Leonard...

1098
01:01:18,356 --> 01:01:21,203
how much I missed him
and loved him...

1099
01:01:21,235 --> 01:01:24,082
and all the terrific times
we'd spent together.

1100
01:01:24,115 --> 01:01:27,627
It was really
a very painful time for me.

1101
01:01:27,665 --> 01:01:31,974
The year ends,
and Zelig is still missing.

1102
01:01:35,216 --> 01:01:37,549
I just moped around and wept.

1103
01:01:37,583 --> 01:01:40,430
And one night
after a very bad time...

1104
01:01:40,462 --> 01:01:42,829
my sister Meryl said to me...

1105
01:01:42,862 --> 01:01:45,709
"Come on, let's go out
for dinner or a concert."

1106
01:01:45,742 --> 01:01:49,537
I said, "No. I can't do it,"
but she insisted.

1107
01:01:49,581 --> 01:01:52,776
We went out
and ended up in a movie.

1108
01:01:52,812 --> 01:01:56,291
We saw "Grand Hotel," and
with it, there was a newsreel.

1109
01:02:05,768 --> 01:02:08,637
Adolf Hitler and
the National Socialist Party...

1110
01:02:08,679 --> 01:02:11,526
continue to consolidate gains
in depression-ridden Berlin.

1111
01:02:11,558 --> 01:02:13,762
Denouncing
the Treaty of Versailles...

1112
01:02:13,798 --> 01:02:17,375
the Nazis make fervent appeals
to German patriotism...

1113
01:02:17,414 --> 01:02:21,122
Eudora Fletcher is stunned
by what she sees.

1114
01:02:21,156 --> 01:02:23,043
Amongst the brown shirts...

1115
01:02:23,076 --> 01:02:25,922
she spots a figure
who could be Zelig.

1116
01:02:25,955 --> 01:02:29,270
Then it made all
the sense in the world...

1117
01:02:29,314 --> 01:02:32,161
because although
he wanted to be loved...

1118
01:02:32,194 --> 01:02:34,081
craved to be loved...

1119
01:02:34,113 --> 01:02:36,480
there was also
something in him...

1120
01:02:36,512 --> 01:02:40,439
that desired immersion
in the mass and anonymity.

1121
01:02:40,480 --> 01:02:43,610
And Fascism offered Zelig
that kind of opportunity...

1122
01:02:43,647 --> 01:02:47,923
so that he could make something
anonymous of himself...

1123
01:02:47,966 --> 01:02:52,438
by belonging
to this vast movement.

1124
01:02:52,476 --> 01:02:55,824
She sails for
Europe the following week.

1125
01:02:55,868 --> 01:02:58,714
Ten days later,
she arrives in Berlin.

1126
01:02:58,747 --> 01:03:03,023
Germany is a country deep
in the throes of the Depression.

1127
01:03:03,066 --> 01:03:06,448
Militarism and unrest
are in the air.

1128
01:03:06,489 --> 01:03:08,910
She searches everywhere
and makes inquiries...

1129
01:03:08,952 --> 01:03:10,381
but it is impossible.

1130
01:03:10,424 --> 01:03:11,766
After three weeks...

1131
01:03:11,800 --> 01:03:14,166
the authorities begin
to get suspicious.

1132
01:03:14,199 --> 01:03:15,606
They watch her.

1133
01:03:15,639 --> 01:03:18,955
While she is out,
they search her hotel room.

1134
01:03:18,998 --> 01:03:20,852
A fourth week goes by...

1135
01:03:20,886 --> 01:03:23,187
and she is about
to give up and go home...

1136
01:03:23,221 --> 01:03:27,498
when news of a large rally
at Munich catches her attention.

1137
01:03:27,540 --> 01:03:29,427
It is rumored
that it will be...

1138
01:03:29,459 --> 01:03:32,306
the largest gathering to date
of Nazi personnel.

1139
01:03:32,339 --> 01:03:34,542
Eudora Fletcher
is counting on the hope...

1140
01:03:34,578 --> 01:03:39,596
that Zelig may attend and that
if she can confront him...

1141
01:03:39,633 --> 01:03:44,073
the strong feeling he has always
had for her can be awakened.

1142
01:03:44,112 --> 01:03:46,500
At first, all appears hopeless.

1143
01:03:46,543 --> 01:03:48,452
The crowd is huge.

1144
01:03:48,495 --> 01:03:51,941
It seems impossible to locate
any one particular face.

1145
01:04:06,155 --> 01:04:09,002
Then suddenly, a figure flanking
the chancellor...

1146
01:04:09,034 --> 01:04:10,659
catches her attention.

1147
01:04:10,698 --> 01:04:15,137
Behind and to the right
of Hitler, she spots Zelig.

1148
01:04:15,176 --> 01:04:19,070
Struggling to make contact,
she manages to catch his eye.

1149
01:04:19,111 --> 01:04:23,420
Like a man emerging
from a dream, Zelig notices her.

1150
01:04:23,462 --> 01:04:27,739
In a matter of seconds,
everything comes back to him.

1151
01:05:23,767 --> 01:05:26,222
It was nothing like
it happened in the movie.

1152
01:05:26,263 --> 01:05:30,637
When Leonard left the podium,
they didn't know what to think.

1153
01:05:30,678 --> 01:05:32,620
We couldn't believe our eyes.

1154
01:05:32,661 --> 01:05:34,548
Hitler's speech was ruined.

1155
01:05:34,581 --> 01:05:38,224
He wanted to make
a good joke about Poland...

1156
01:05:38,260 --> 01:05:42,536
but just then,
Zelig interfered...

1157
01:05:42,579 --> 01:05:46,375
and Hitler was extremely upset.

1158
01:05:46,418 --> 01:05:52,080
The SS wanted to grab Zelig...

1159
01:05:52,113 --> 01:05:54,959
but if they would have
grabbed him...

1160
01:05:54,992 --> 01:05:57,838
they probably would have
tortured him...

1161
01:05:57,871 --> 01:06:00,237
or maybe even shot him.

1162
01:06:00,271 --> 01:06:01,678
So in the confusion...

1163
01:06:01,710 --> 01:06:05,026
Fletcher and Zelig
got out of the building...

1164
01:06:05,070 --> 01:06:06,957
through a side door.

1165
01:06:06,989 --> 01:06:10,305
They grabbed a car,
sped away in the car...

1166
01:06:10,348 --> 01:06:13,064
and the SS after them,
shot them.

1167
01:06:14,060 --> 01:06:16,001
In rare
German newsreel footage...

1168
01:06:16,042 --> 01:06:18,911
a quick glimpse of the escape
was recorded.

1169
01:06:32,358 --> 01:06:35,205
I was flying.
It was wonderful.

1170
01:06:35,238 --> 01:06:37,604
And then suddenly,
something happened.

1171
01:06:37,638 --> 01:06:40,004
I was frightened.
I lost control.

1172
01:06:40,037 --> 01:06:41,923
We went into a dive.

1173
01:06:41,956 --> 01:06:46,014
Leonard was so terrified that
he changed his personality...

1174
01:06:46,051 --> 01:06:49,847
and before my eyes,
because I was a pilot...

1175
01:06:49,890 --> 01:06:51,995
he turned into one, too.

1176
01:06:52,034 --> 01:06:54,684
Zelig takes control
of the airplane.

1177
01:06:54,722 --> 01:06:56,609
Acting the role of pilot...

1178
01:06:56,641 --> 01:06:59,096
he struggles valiantly
with the aircraft.

1179
01:06:59,136 --> 01:07:02,997
The Germans, who are stunned,
take a full fifteen minutes...

1180
01:07:03,039 --> 01:07:05,756
before following
in hot pursuit of their quarry.

1181
01:07:05,791 --> 01:07:07,798
With Eudora Fletcher
unconscious...

1182
01:07:07,838 --> 01:07:10,685
Zelig, who had never flown
before in his life...

1183
01:07:10,717 --> 01:07:13,084
not only escapes
the German pilots...

1184
01:07:13,117 --> 01:07:16,913
but sets a record for flying
nonstop across the Atlantic...

1185
01:07:16,956 --> 01:07:18,385
upside down.

1186
01:07:38,679 --> 01:07:41,013
With a storm of cheers
and a blizzard of ticker tape...

1187
01:07:41,046 --> 01:07:43,729
New York welcomes back
Eudora Fletcher...

1188
01:07:43,765 --> 01:07:46,285
and Leonard Zelig,
the human chameleon.

1189
01:07:46,325 --> 01:07:50,153
His remarkable feat of aviation
fills the nation with pride...

1190
01:07:50,196 --> 01:07:52,716
and earns him
a full presidential pardon.

1191
01:07:52,755 --> 01:07:54,348
Forgiving multitudes
flock to see him...

1192
01:07:54,387 --> 01:07:57,201
as he sits by the side
of his plucky bride-to-be.

1193
01:07:57,234 --> 01:07:59,208
Their journey of triumph
leads to City Hall.

1194
01:07:59,249 --> 01:08:02,096
New York's greatest honor,
the Medal of Valor...

1195
01:08:02,129 --> 01:08:04,975
is bestowed on Zelig
by Carter Dean.

1196
01:08:05,008 --> 01:08:09,741
You are a great inspiration
to the young of this nation...

1197
01:08:09,775 --> 01:08:12,141
who will one day grow up...

1198
01:08:12,174 --> 01:08:15,021
and be great doctors
and great patients.

1199
01:08:22,731 --> 01:08:24,618
This was a great thrill.

1200
01:08:24,651 --> 01:08:27,498
I'm glad we lived
to see this day.

1201
01:08:27,530 --> 01:08:30,377
Right. I've never flown
before in my life...

1202
01:08:30,409 --> 01:08:33,256
and it shows exactly
what you can do...

1203
01:08:33,289 --> 01:08:35,198
if you're a total psychotic.

1204
01:08:39,848 --> 01:08:42,149
The thing was paradoxical...

1205
01:08:42,183 --> 01:08:45,498
because what enabled him to
perform this astounding feat...

1206
01:08:45,542 --> 01:08:49,022
was his ability
to transform himself.

1207
01:08:49,061 --> 01:08:53,817
Therefore, his sickness was also
at the root of his salvation...

1208
01:08:53,860 --> 01:08:57,656
and I think it's interesting
to view the thing that way.

1209
01:08:57,699 --> 01:09:03,546
It was his very disorder
that made a hero of him.

1210
01:09:03,586 --> 01:09:06,520
It was really absurd in a way.

1211
01:09:06,561 --> 01:09:09,408
I mean, he had
this curious quirk...

1212
01:09:09,441 --> 01:09:11,164
this strange characteristic.

1213
01:09:11,200 --> 01:09:13,566
And for a time,
everyone loved him...

1214
01:09:13,599 --> 01:09:15,965
and then people
stopped loving him.

1215
01:09:15,999 --> 01:09:18,845
Then he did this stunt
with the airplane...

1216
01:09:18,878 --> 01:09:21,244
and then everybody
loved him again.

1217
01:09:21,277 --> 01:09:24,124
And that was what
the twenties were like.

1218
01:09:24,156 --> 01:09:27,701
When you think about it,
has America changed so much?

1219
01:09:27,740 --> 01:09:29,627
I don't think so.

1220
01:09:29,660 --> 01:09:34,099
After untangling
countless legal details...

1221
01:09:34,138 --> 01:09:37,454
Leonard Zelig
and Eudora Fletcher marry.

1222
01:09:37,497 --> 01:09:41,555
It is a simple ceremony
captured on home movies.

1223
01:09:59,636 --> 01:10:03,596
"Wanting only to be liked,
he distorted himself...

1224
01:10:03,635 --> 01:10:06,155
"beyond measure,"
wrote Scott Fitzgerald.

1225
01:10:06,194 --> 01:10:09,193
"One wonders what would have
happened if at the outset...

1226
01:10:09,234 --> 01:10:13,989
"he had had the courage to speak
his mind and not pretend.

1227
01:10:14,032 --> 01:10:17,960
"In the end, it was, after all,
not the approbation of many...

1228
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:22,636
"but the love of one woman
that changed his life."

